    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6596e67e_6bd0b84f",
        "filename": "util/linux/memory_map_test.cc",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 299,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-24T14:44:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Why don’t you make the ReadPipeHandle() non-blocking in the child, and try to read a byte from it? If you see EAGAIN, the parent’s still alive. If you read 0 (EOF), the parent’s gone, either because it died or because it closed its end of the pipe because it was done with the test. Any other result is unexpected and the child should ASSERT or FAIL out.",
      "revId": "bf45ada33a432caf27bc795e6b55a10ca7cd9b70",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
